Title: Linking forum posts - classicalcomp-001-1-T1.1

Keywords: tagging, categorization, discussion forum, forum threads, mooc
Input.threadtitle: Is the ii7 chord in Diatonic Minor diminished or half-dimished?
Input.posts:
In lesson 1, Dr. Ed says that ii7 is a a diminished seventh chord but I checked it and it seems to me that it's a half-diminished seventh since it has the notes D, F, Ab, C being 1, b3, b5, b7 and not bb7. Am I missing something?
Upvotes:
3
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
Yes, this is true.  It's a mistake on my part.  Thanks for catching it.
Instructor's post : Yes, this is true.  It's a mistake on my part.  Thanks for catching it.
Upvotes:
1

Input.threadtitle: Lesson 1 06:20 - does there close structure resolve to an opened one?
Input.posts:
Hi guys. I think at 06:20 exists example of switching of voicing from closed structure to opened one. Is this correct? My proposal - to maintain closed one and keeping common tone is DAfa. Am I correct? But I am not sure if parallel movement of the Base and the Alt of 1m is correct? (B:C#-D and A:e-f)
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
Hi Jerzy. Yes, it is an example of switching from closed structure to an opened one. With your suggestion, there is no parallel movement involved, but in your suggestion, you would be doubling the fifth (the A) for a chord i. It is acceptable, but doubling the root would be preferred.
Instructor's post : Hi Jerzy. Yes, it is an example of switching from closed structure to an opened one. It is acceptable, but doubling the root would be preferred.

Input.posts:
On the iv chord in bar 2 (5 mins into the video), while using the common tone approach (here the note G between Gm and Cm Prof. Edwards investigates 2 possibilities : either keep the G in the tenor or in the soprano... is there any stylistic guideline or rule that says we shouldn't keep both Gs using the common tone approach ? While drilling myself, here's what I thought was a clean answer : Is it mandatory to double the root ? Here I doubled the fifth, but the voice leading seems fine, no ? Here is my resulting cadential 6/4 : Doesn't sound as good I reckon.
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
Hi Julien and Andi. Julien, yes doubling the fifth is fine. But what about your i6-4 chord? You have doubled the 5th, yes, but the third is omitted in that chord, and this is unacceptable. 
Instructor's post : Hi Julien and Andi. Julien, yes doubling the fifth is fine. But what about your i6-4 chord? You have doubled the 5th, yes, but the third is omitted in that chord, and this is unacceptable.

Input.threadtitle: Resolving leading tone in inner voices
Input.posts:
Does leading tone only needs to be resolve to tonic when it is in the outer voices? How do you resolve the leading tone when it is in the inner voices? Thanks
Upvotes:
1
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
Yes, leading tones in the outer voices will need to resolve to the tonic. Leading tones in the inner voices however do not have to resolve to the tonic as they are less exposed as compared to outer voices. With leading tones in the inner voices, if you are in a V-I progression, you can have the option of moving into the dominant, which is the fifth of the V chord. This will be the next chord tone to move to in the smallest interval possible after the tonic.
